        <div class="summary-paragraph"><strong>Introduction:</strong> "The Little Girl" by Katherine Mansfield is a touching story that explores the relationship between a young girl named Kezia and her father. The story highlights how children sometimes misunderstand their parents and fail to recognize the love hidden behind strict behavior.</div>

        <div class="summary-paragraph"><strong>Kezia's Fear of Her Father:</strong> Kezia was a timid and sensitive child who was afraid of her father. He was a strict, serious, and hardworking man who rarely expressed his emotions openly. Whenever he spoke to her, she became nervous and stammered. As a result, she believed that her father was harsh and did not love her.</div>

        <div class="summary-paragraph"><strong>The Pin-Cushion Incident:</strong> Kezia's grandmother encouraged her to become closer to her father. To show her love, Kezia decided to make a pin-cushion as a birthday gift for him. While looking for material to fill it, she tore up some papers from her father's room, unaware that they contained an important speech he had prepared for work. When her father discovered this, he became angry and punished her with a ruler. This incident increased Kezia's fear and resentment toward him.</div>

        <div class="summary-paragraph"><strong>The Macdonald Family:</strong> Living next door was the Macdonald family. Mr. Macdonald was cheerful and affectionate toward his five children. He played with them and openly showed his love. Seeing this, Kezia wished that her own father would behave in a similar manner. She compared the two fathers and felt disappointed by her father's strict nature.</div>

        <div class="summary-paragraph"><strong>The Night of the Nightmare:</strong> One night, when Kezia's mother was ill and her grandmother was away, she had to sleep alone. During the night, she woke up terrified after a frightening nightmare. Crying and trembling with fear, she called for help.</div>

        <div class="summary-paragraph"><strong>Father's Hidden Love:</strong> Hearing her cries, Kezia's father immediately came to her room. He picked her up, carried her to his bed, and comforted her until she felt safe again. For the first time, Kezia experienced her father's warmth and protection. She realized how hard he worked every day and understood that he loved her deeply, even though he did not express it openly.</div>

        <div class="summary-paragraph"><strong>Change in Kezia's Understanding:</strong> After this experience, Kezia's opinion of her father completely changed. She no longer saw him as a cruel giant. Instead, she recognized him as a caring and responsible parent who sacrificed his comfort for the happiness of his family.</div>

        <div class="summary-paragraph"><strong>Conclusion:</strong> The story teaches that parents often express love in different ways. While some show affection openly, others demonstrate their love through hard work, sacrifice, and responsibility. "The Little Girl" emphasizes the importance of understanding family members and looking beyond outward appearances to recognize true love and care.</div>
